data.describe() provides statistical insights into numerical columns, offering metrics like mean (average), standard deviation (a measure of data spread), and quartiles (dividing the data into four parts).

0.4 Measure of central tendency

Measures of central tendency provides information about the âcenterâ or typical value of a dataset. We will delve deeper into understanding the distribution and variability of our data by calculating (mean, median) for the âMS SubClassâ column.
- Mean: The mean is the average value of a dataset .

  • Median: The median is the middle value of a dataset when it is sorted in ascending order. It is less affected by extreme values than the mean.
data["MS SubClass"].mean()
#This gives us sense of where most data points cluster around
57.38737201365188
data["MS SubClass"].median()
50.0

0.5 Measure dispersion

This describes how spread out or scattered a set of data is.It provides information about the variability or diversity of the data points in the dataset.

  • Range: The range is the difference between the maximum and minimum values in a dataset, providing insight into the spread of the data.

  • Variance: Variance measures how much the values in a dataset vary. It is the average of the squared differences from the Mean.

  • Standard Deviation: Standard deviation quantifies the amount of variation or dispersion of a set of values. It is the square root of the variance.

We will look at the dispersion for the Ms SubClass column

ms_subclass_range = data["MS SubClass"].max()- data["MS SubClass"].min()
ms_subclass_range
170
data["MS SubClass"].var()
1818.0011378506483
data["MS SubClass"].std()
42.6380245538023

0.6 Missing Values

When analyzing data, encountering missing values is a common scenario that requires careful management. Addressing these gaps is crucial before delving into the analysis process.

0.7 Approaches to Handle Missing Data

0.7.1 Imputation

  • This involves filling in missing columns with estimated values based on the available data
  • Different approach available from simple to complex

0.7.2 Deletion

  • This involves deleting an entire record (row) if a value is missing
  • Data can be reduced significantly
  • If values are not missing at random, can introduce significant bias

0.7.3 Identifying missing data

After identifying missing values, it is often crucial to focus on columns with a substantial amount of missing data. We will create a variable called filter_columnswhere we will store columns that contain more than one missing value. We will sort this by descending order. So we will have high number of missing value on top.

missing_values = data.isna().sum() 
filter_columns = missing_values[(missing_values >1)].sort_values(ascending=False)

0.7.4 Imputation

Filling missing values with statistics: We can fill missing value with summary statistics such as mean, median, mode among others.

Median is often used to fill missing value (i) it is not influenced by extreme values or outliers in data. (ii) it helps to preserve the overall distribution of the data.

We will impute missing value in Mas Vnr Area column with mean value. To do this, we will first create a variable called mean_value_mvawhere we will calculate the average value using the .mean method. The round() function is used to round the mean value to two decimal place for consistency.

# Filling in missing value 

mean_value_mva= round (data["Mas Vnr Area"].mean(), ndigits=2)

The fillnamethod replaces the missing value in the Mas Vnr Area column with this calculated mean. Imputation helps maintain the datasetâs overall statistical properties. The inplace=True ensures that the change is applied directly to the dataset.

data["Mas Vnr Area"].fillna(mean_value_mva, inplace=True)

Now we will look at the Mas Vnr Area column to ensure missing value has been handled.

data["Mas Vnr Area"].isna().sum()
0

0.7.5 Deletion

Sometimes, certain columns might have a large number if missing values or might not be relevant to the analysis.In such cases, dropping the entire columns is a viable option. Here the Pool QC column is removed from the dataset using the .drop()method, The axis=1 parameter specifies that the operation is performed on columns.

data.drop("Pool QC", axis=1, inplace=True)

0.8 Data Visualisation

Visualization is a powerful tool in data analysis, allowing us to grasp patterns and trends more intuitively. We used the Matplotlib library to create a histogram, a common visualization for understanding the distribution of a dataset.

  • Histogram: A histogram is a graphical representation of the distribution of numerical data. It is an estimate of the probability distribution of a continuous variable.
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data["SalePrice"].hist(bins=20)
plt.xlabel("House Price in $")
plt.title("Distribution of the house price in Ames ");

The histogram illustrates the frequency of house prices in the dataset, offering an immediate visual sense of how prices are distributed.

0.8.1 Data Visualization - Mean Price by Neighborhood

Lastly, we will employe data visualization techniques to explore relationships within the dataset. We calculate the mean house price for each neighborhood and represented the results using a horizontal bar chart.

  • Bar Chart: A bar chart (or bar graph) presents categorical data with rectangular bars. The length of each bar is proportional to the value it represents.
# calculate mean price by  neighbourhood
mean_price_by_neighbourhood = data.groupby('Neighborhood')['SalePrice'].mean()
mean_price_by_neighbourhood.plot(kind="barh",rot=0, color="blue", figsize=(20,30))
plt.xlabel("Neighbourhood")
plt.ylabel("Mean Price")
plt.title("Mean price by neighbourhood")
plt.show()

This visualization offers insights into how house prices vary across different neighborhoods, providing valuable information for real estate analysis.

In summary, this session provided a comprehensive overview of essential data analysis techniques, from data loading and exploration to summary statistics, handling missing data and data visualisation. These foundational skills are indispensable for anyone working with real-world datasets, enabling them to uncover patters, make informed decision, and draw meaningful conclusions from data.
